In a situation like this:

    stringStack.push( stringStack.pop()); 

You just have to keep in mind that `push` has to know what value to push, before the value is pushed. How does it know what value to push? Evaluating `pop()`, of course! So an item is popped first, then `push` knows what item to push, and pushes to back. In other words, A `pop` inside a `push` overall does nothing to the stack.

What about:

    stringStack.push( stringStack.peek());

Instead of popping the top item off and then pushing it, this will only _look at_ the top item, and then pushes it onto the stack. So overall this is just &quot;copying&quot; the top item.

Here is what the stack looks like after each line (left is the top):

    stringStack.push( “Jane” ); 
    // Jane
    stringStack.push( “Jess” ); 
    // Jess Jane
    stringStack.push( “Jill” ); 
    // Jill Jess Jane
    stringStack.push( stringStack.pop()); 
    // Jill Jess Jane
    stringStack.push( stringStack.peek()); 
    // Jill Jill Jess Jane
    stringStack.push( “Jim” ); 
    // Jim Jill Jill Jess Jane
    String name = stringStack.pop(); 
    // Jill Jill Jess Jane
    stringStack.push( stringStack.peek());
    // Jill Jill Jill Jess Jane

