A neat trick in this scenario is to create a separate (custom) SQL Server role that can only execute stored procedures:

    CREATE ROLE db_executor;
	GRANT EXECUTE TO db_executor;

This role now has the permission to execute *any* stored procedure in the database in which it&#39;s been created - and in addition: that permission will also extend to any *future* stored procedures you might create later on in this database.

Now create a user in your database and give it *only* this database role - this user will only be able to execute stored procedures - any and all of them in your database.

If you user should be allowed to execute any and all stored procedures - this is a very convenient way to allow this (and you don&#39;t have to constantly update the permissions when new stored procedures are created).

